prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The typical linewidth in low-mass protostars is ~1 km/s (Jorgensen et al. 2007). We ask for a spectral resolution of 0.1 km/s to resolve as much velocity structure as possible in the brightest sources. In weaker sources, we can smooth the spectra to 1 km/s to achieve the requested sensitivity.
Our primary target is C18O 2-1. In order to increase the scientific value and maximize the chance of serendipitous discoveries, we set additional spectral windows on 13CO 2-1 and DCO+ 3-2. Both are commonly observed in protostars. Lastly, we dedicate one full baseband to continuum.

According to Fig. 2, we have to resolve CO snowlines down to about 100 AU for 1 Lsun protostars. This corresponds to 0.43" in Perseus. We expect the largest CO snowlines to lie at a radius of about 1000 AU (Fig. 2), setting a largest angular scale of 8.5".

According to Fig. 2, we have to resolve CO snowlines down to about 100 AU for 1 Lsun protostars. This corresponds to 0.43" in Perseus. If we rescale the C18O 2-1 intensities from the SMA (Jorgensen et al. 2015) to this smaller beam, we expect peak fluxes for the weakest sources of 43 mJy. Our radiative transfer models from Visser et al. (2015) predict similar line intensities. We request a sensitivity of 8.6 mJy to ensure at least 5sigma detections.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
Snowlines are the locations where molecules like H2O and CO freeze out onto dust grains. According to laboratory experiments, the CO snowline occurs somewhere between 20 and 30 K, depending on the ice composition. However, the actual CO evaporation temperature in a protostar has never been measured, nor are there any data on possible source-to-source variations.
We propose to resolve the CO snowlines in a sample of 57 low-mass protostars, using C18O 2-1 and 3-2. These lines will allow us to measure the excitation temperature right at the snowline, and because of the low critical density, this translates directly into a measurement of the evaporation temperature of CO. Simultaneously, we will compare the locations of the snowlines to where we expect them to be based on the protostellar luminosities. Previous observations with the SMA showed extended C18O emission in 8 of 16 protostars. This suggests they were warmer in the past -- presumably due to an accretion burst -- and CO is still in the process of refreezing. Our proposed ALMA observations will significantly extend the statistics of this phenomenon.
